body: What numpy version are you using, and how was it installed (conda or pip)? The output from 'conda list' would be helpful to determine this.

This was fresh install of Anaconda3 I also updated numpy with the same error. This is from conda list:

```
numpy                     1.15.4           py37h19fb1c0_0
numpy-base                1.15.4           py37hc3f5095_0
```

Also, I have not install `onnx` itself because it is giving me error:

```
$ pip install onnx
Collecting onnx
  Using cached https://files.pythonhosted.org/packages/59/09/61f817a530cd9b9bd0e289bc9cda46f662fcda4dc1bd687b36d45365e3ea/onnx-1.4.1.tar.gz
    Complete output from command python setup.py egg_info:
    fatal: not a git repository (or any of the parent directories): .git
    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File "<string>", line 1, in <module>
      File "C:\Users\ehazar\AppData\Local\Temp\pip-install-sopv5lb_\onnx\setup.py", line 71, in <module>
        assert CMAKE, 'Could not find "cmake" executable!'
    AssertionError: Could not find "cmake" executable!

    ----------------------------------------
Command "python setup.py egg_info" failed with error code 1 in C:\Users\ehazar\AppData\Local\Temp\pip-install-sopv5lb_\onnx\
```

Tries to compile (perhaps no wheel for Windows?)

> I also updated numpy with the same error.

That would strongly suggest it's an issue with the numpy install. You could try uninstalling and reinstalling numpy. If you can't import numpy into python, the issue is below onnxruntime.

I can import numpy fine

```
$ ipython
Python 3.7.1 (default, Dec 10 2018, 22:54:23) [MSC v.1915 64 bit (AMD64)]
Type 'copyright', 'credits' or 'license' for more information
IPython 7.2.0 -- An enhanced Interactive Python. Type '?' for help.

In [1]: import numpy as np
```

What about `onnx`? isn't that a dependency? I guess it has no wheels installs for Windows

I believe there's a binary install. 
`conda install -c conda-forge onnx`
Ok I did `pip install --upgrade numpy` and now I have `numpy-1.16.1` and that fixed the issue. I think you should add `numpy >= 1.16` to your requirements
`conda install -c conda-forge onnx` does install onnx, but it also downgrades numpy to 1.15, I wonder why there is a hard requirement to 1.15

huh it also downgraded the entire python py37 to py36 (I wonder why conda even allows that!) and installs conda-forge/win-64::onnx-1.1.1-py36_0 

What is a working environment to try onnxruntime in Python? what is the suggested Python version, ...?

hi sorry for replying late:
1. for onnxruntime numpy issue: yes it is a known issue. upgrading to latest numpy version will solve it. we are looking into it.
2. for onnx: currently conda-forge did not have a 3.7 protobuf package. We suggest u working on python 3.6 with conda installed 3.5.2 version protobuf library. 3.6.1 protobuf for python 3.6 is also missing some symbols. We are thinking of switching to build protobuf lib on the fly instead of using shipped binary soon. see https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/appveyor.yml for steps. 

Thanks ðŸ˜ƒ
I had the same problem. Uninstalling numpy 1.15.3 and installing numpy 1.16.1 solved it for me (it also solved the segfault issue I was having).

Started with a miniconda
Installed a py36 conda environment, 

    conda create --name py36 python=3.6 anaconda

and upgraded numpy 
   
    pip install --upgrade numpy

Then I can install and import both

    pip install onnx
    pip install onnxruntime

issue.title: Segfault with scikit-learn LogisticRegression model

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**

I get a segfault with running inference on the logistic regression model generated with sklearn-onnx

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution: Ubuntu 18.10"
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary (conda)
- ONNX Runtime version: 0.2.1
- Python version: 3.7
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source):
- CUDA/cuDNN version: None
- GPU model and memory: None

Full versions can be found below,

**To Reproduce**
Loosely adapted from http://onnx.ai/sklearn-onnx/ example
```py
import numpy as np

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

import onnxruntime as rt

from skl2onnx import convert_sklearn
from skl2onnx.common.data_types import FloatTensorType

rng = np.random.RandomState(42)

n_features = 20
X = rng.rand(1000, n_features)
y = rng.randint(2, size=(1000,))

estimator = LogisticRegression(solver="lbfgs")
estimator.fit(X, y)

initial_type = [('float_input', FloatTensorType([1, n_features]))]
onx = convert_sklearn(estimator, initial_types=initial_type)
with open('./estimator.onnx', "wb") as f:
    f.write(onx.SerializeToString())

sess = rt.InferenceSession("estimator.onnx")
input_name = sess.get_inputs()[0].name
label_name = sess.get_outputs()[0].name
pred_onx = sess.run([label_name], {input_name: X.astype(np.float32)})[0]
```

**Expected behavior**
Some predictions no segfault.
